<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900823-0009</DOCNO><DOCID>900823-0009.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   David Sarnoff Center,   Two Electronics Firms   Win Defense Contract</HL><DATE>08/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   SUNW TXN</CO><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   PRINCETON, N.J. -- The David Sarnoff Research Center saidit and two major electronics companies were awarded a $7.7million contract from the Defense Department to develop ahigh-resolution video workstation.   The new workstation, which would combine capabilities forhandling text, video and graphics in a high-powered computer,will be developed by the Sarnoff Center along with SunMicrosystems Inc., Mountain View, Calif., and TexasInstruments Inc., Dallas. The Sarnoff Center is a unit of SRIInternational, a contract-based research and consulting firmbased in Menlo Park, Calif.</LP><TEXT>   The military would likely use such a computer as abuilding block for &quot;combat information systems,&quot; a Sarnoffspokesman said. He said the basic technology would also havenumerous commercial uses, including video teleconferencingand medical imaging.   Separately, the Sarnoff Center said it was awarded a $3million contract for a supercomputer dedicated to processingvideo information.   Both awards, administered through the Defense AdvancedResearch Projects Agency, were originally announced lastOctober, but no dollar amounts were specified at that time.</TEXT></DOC>